$(x,y)^T$$(x,y,1)^T$

Affine Transformation

$$\mathbf{T}(\mathbf{x}) = \mathbf{A} \cdot \mathbf{x} + \mathbf{b}$$

  • $\mathbf{x} = \begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \end{pmatrix}$
  • $\mathbf{A} = \begin{pmatrix} t_{11} & t_{12} \\ t_{21} & t_{22} \end{pmatrix}$ $2 \times 2$
  • $\mathbf{b} = \begin{pmatrix} b_x \\ b_y \end{pmatrix}$

$\begin{pmatrix} t_{11} & t_{12} & b_x \\ t_{21} & t_{22} & b_y \\ 0 & 0 & 0 \end{pmatrix}$

Perspective Transformation

$3 \times 3$ $\mathbf{H} = \begin{pmatrix} h_{11} & h_{12} & h_{13} \\ h_{21} & h_{22} & h_{23} \\ h_{31} & h_{32} & h_{33} \end{pmatrix}$

$$\begin{pmatrix} x' \\ y' \\ w' \end{pmatrix} = \mathbf{H} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}$$

$(x', y')^T$

$$x' = \frac{x'}{w'}, \quad y' = \frac{y'}{w'}$$

Fourier Transform

$f(x, y)$ $F(u, v)$

$$ F(u, v) = \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} f(x, y) e^{-j 2\pi (ux + vy)} \, dx \, dy $$

PILtransformmethod=Transform.AFFINE6

In[]:
def affine_trans(pic: Image.Image, T: np.ndarray, b: np.ndarray) -> Image.Image:
    inv_T = np.linalg.inv(T)
    inv_b = -b
    data = np.concatenate((inv_T, inv_b.reshape(2, 1)), axis=1).flatten()
    pic = pic.transform(pic.size, Image.AFFINE, data, Image.BICUBIC)
    return pic

method=Transform.PERSPECTIVE8

In[]:
def perspective_trans(pic: Image.Image, H: np.ndarray) -> Image.Image:
    inv_H = np.linalg.inv(H)
    data = inv_H.flatten()[:8]
    pic = pic.transform(pic.size, Image.PERSPECTIVE, data, Image.BICUBIC)
    return pic

import numpy as np
from scipy.interpolate import griddata

def interpolate(freq: np.ndarray, mask: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:
    """
    Interpolates the masked regions in a frequency array using neighboring non-masked pixels.

    Args:
        freq (np.ndarray): The frequency array.
        mask (np.ndarray): A binary mask array where 1 represents the masked regions to interpolate.

    Returns:
        np.ndarray: The interpolated frequency array.
    """
    # Get the coordinates of the masked (noisy) and non-masked (valid) regions
    masked_coords = np.argwhere(mask == 1)  # Coordinates where mask is 1 (masked area)
    valid_coords = np.argwhere(mask == 0)   # Coordinates where mask is 0 (valid area)
    
    # Get frequency values at the non-masked (valid) coordinates
    valid_values = freq[mask == 0]

    # Use griddata to interpolate the masked regions
    interpolated_values = griddata(valid_coords, valid_values, masked_coords, method='nearest')
    
    # Handle NaN values (if any) by using nearest-neighbor interpolation as a fallback
    nan_mask = np.isnan(interpolated_values)
    if np.any(nan_mask):
        interpolated_values[nan_mask] = griddata(valid_coords, valid_values, masked_coords[nan_mask], method='nearest')
    
    # Create a copy of the frequency array and fill in the interpolated values in the masked area
    freq_interp = freq.copy()
    for i, (x, y) in enumerate(masked_coords):
        freq_interp[x, y] = interpolated_values[i]

    return freq_interp

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from numpy.fft import fft2, ifft2, fftshift, ifftshift
from PIL import Image

# Load the image and convert to grayscale
img = Image.open('lena.png').convert('L')
img = np.array(img)

# Perform 2D FFT
freq = fftshift(fft2(img))
x_c, y_c = img.shape[0] // 2, img.shape[1] // 2

# Create a mask where 1 indicates noise and 0 indicates valid data
mask = np.ones_like(img)
w_b = 1 # Width of the band
y_1 = -123
x_1 = 50
y_2 = 124
x_2 = -50
x_3 = -50
x_4 = 50
y_5 = -170
y_6 = 170

mask = np.zeros_like(img, dtype=np.uint8)
mask[x_c+x_1:, y_c+y_1-w_b:y_c+y_1+w_b] = 1
mask[:x_c-x_1, y_c+y_1-w_b:y_c+y_1+w_b] = 1
mask[x_c+x_2:, y_c+y_2-w_b:y_c+y_2+w_b] = 1
mask[:x_c+x_2, y_c+y_2-w_b:y_c+y_2+w_b] = 1
mask[:x_c+x_3, y_c] = 1
mask[x_c+x_4:, y_c] = 1
mask[x_c-w_b+1:x_c+w_b+1, :y_c+y_5] = 1
mask[x_c-w_b-4:x_c+w_b, y_c+y_6:] = 1

# Apply interpolation to the masked regions
freq_interp = interpolate(freq, mask)

# Perform inverse FFT to get the filtered image
filtered_freq = ifftshift(freq_interp)
img_filtered = ifft2(filtered_freq).real

# Clip values and convert to uint8
img_filtered = np.clip(img_filtered, 0, 255).astype(np.uint8)

# 2x2 Subplots
fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 12))

# Original frequency spectrum
axs[0, 0].imshow(np.log(1 + np.abs(freq)))
axs[0, 0].set_title('Original Frequency Spectrum')

# Interpolated frequency spectrum
axs[0, 1].imshow(np.log(1 + np.abs(freq_interp)))
axs[0, 1].set_title('Interpolated Frequency Spectrum')

# Original and filtered image
axs[1, 0].imshow(img, cmap='gray')
axs[1, 0].set_title('Original Image')
axs[1, 1].imshow(img_filtered, cmap='gray')
axs[1, 1].set_title('Filtered Image')

plt.show()
